Trenton impressed again in Week 6, racking up four solos, five assists, 0.5 sacks, and one pass defended. This was the Ravens' linebackers' second strong start in a row, and one has to wonder where this production was before he got replaced as a starter. With that said, Trenton makes for a solid LB3 option if Roquan Smith (hamstring) misses more time in Week 8. Start him if the Ravens' superstar linebacker misses another contest.

Gary was excellent in Week 7, reeling off two solos, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Gary has upped his sack count to 5.5 sacks, with at least one sack in four of his six contests. Gary is a premier pass rusher who should be rostered in all competitive leagues. Start Gary as a DL2 option for a plus Week 8 matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers. Make the add everywhere.

Baker showed up in Week 7, racking up one solo, three assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Baker played just 28 percent of the snaps in Week 7 and will not be a fantasy option unless there are injuries ahead of him. Keep him on the waiver wire or benches for Week 8 despite the strong production against the hapless Miami Dolphins.

The return of the Mack. Khalil returned from injury to record two solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss in Week 7. Mack is up to two sacks in his three games played this season and should continue to make an impact for IDP managers. He played just 20 percent of the snaps in Week 7, but saw 74 percent when healthy in Week 1, which is more indicative of what we can expect from him when he is ready for a heavier workload. Tap Mack as a DL3 who will fight for top-25 status once his snaps are back to starter level.

Hunt was excellent in Week 7, tallying one solo, one interception, one pass defended, and one touchdown. The pick-six was exciting, but Hunt has been a starter all season and has zero sacks to his name, leaving him far from fantasy relevance. Look elsewhere for Week 8 despite the plus matchup against the New York Giants.

Cross was excellent in Week 7, racking up six solos, one interception, and one pass defended. The Colts' safety has recorded four or more solos in six of his seven games, and five or more in four of them. He is locked in as a DB1 option ahead of a tasty matchup against the Tennessee Titans in Week 8. Tap him as a top-five play at the position, thanks to the plus matchup.

Elliott was at it again in Week 7, notching six solos and three assists. Elliott has registered four or more solos in all four of his starts, producing at a high-end DB2 level thus far. Treat him as such for a plus Week 8 matchup against the Green Bay Packers. Make the add where possible.

Tykee Smith went bonkers in Week 7, ripping off eight solos, five assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Tykee has recorded four or more solos in six of his seven contests and five or more in three of his last four. His monster week pushed him to DB1 overall and in fppg through seven games of the whole season. It's time to take Smith seriously as a top-10 option.

Moehrig was excellent in Week 7, racking up three solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Tre'Von has recorded six or more olos in three of his first five games, and has ridden four spike weeks into the DB2 conversation. Count him as one for a plus Week 8 matchup against the Buffalo Bills.

Metellus was excellent in Week 7, racking up three solos, five assists, 0.5 sacks, and one tackle for loss. Josh has registered four solos in four of his six contests, but has slipped to the DB2/3 realm due to inconsistency in overall production. This was just his second 'spike' week of the season, but he still makes for a top-25 option for a plus Week 8 matchup against the Los Angeles Chargers Week 8 on Thursday Night Football.

Battle was excellent in Week 7, racking up three solos, two assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Jordan has recorded four or more solos in four of his seven contests and is pushing his way towards the DB2 conversation. Riding high from his second-best fantasy output of the season to face off against the New York Jets in Week 8 gives Battle DB2 upside.

Brisker showed up in Week 7, racking up four solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. This was Jaquan's first game with more than two solos since Week 2, but Brisker has recorded a sack and a pick in the last two weeks. Tap Brisker as a matchup-based DB2 option, who is normally a DB3. Treat him as a top-25 option for a plus Week 8 matchup against the Baltimore Ravens. Make the add where needed.

DeJean was at it again in Week 7, reeling off seven solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Cooper has tallied five or more solos in four of his last six games and has put himself in the DB2 mix. However, treat him as a DB3 for Week 8, despite the plus matchup against the New York Giants Week 8, as the talented defensive back laid an egg against New York back in Week 6.

Delpit showed up in Week 7, racking up three solos, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Delpit has slipped to the DB3 realm this season, registering three or fewer solos in five of his seven contests. He has now put together two splash weeks, so he remains a fantasy option for those in deeper leagues. Add Delpit as a bye week filler where needed for a plus Week 8 matchup against the New England Patriots.

Dru Phillips went off in Week 7, piling up nine solos and one tackle for loss. This was his second game with eight or more solos, a stunning number for a corner. Dru is the CB1/DB4 on the season thanks to four spike weeks in seven contests. Tap him as a DB2 with DB1 upside for a plus Week 8 matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Marcus Jones was at it again in Week 7, tallying two solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Jones is on a heater, recording four straight spike weeks with a sack or an interception in each of his last three games. Fire him up as a top-25 option for a tasty Week 8 matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Tyson showed up in Week 7, racking up one solo, one assist, one interception, two passes defended, and one touchdown. It was the first pick of the season for Campbell, who has recorded four or more solos in four of his five games to start the season. Tyson is a top-five in fantasy points through seven weeks of the season. Tyson was the DB5 coming into Week 7 and just had his top fantasy output of the season, boosting him to 'safe to plug in as a DB1 in novelty leagues' realm. Treat him as a DB2 with DB1 upside otherwise for a plus Week 8 matchup against the New England Patriots.

Bland was excellent in Week 7, racking up four solos, two assists, one interception, one pass defended, and one touchdown. This was Bland's first pick of the season, but this marks the third time in the last four contests he's registered four or more solos. Tap him as a top-15 option at CB or a DB3 in DB leagues. Start him everywhere for a plus Week 8 matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Dane Belton was excellent in Week 7, reeling off six solos and four assists. This was his second serviceable fantasy game in two weeks, but it was just his second game with more than two solos. Last week was his first game with more than two solos, making him a DB4 at best. Dane was not much of a fantasy factor prior to Week 6, and is not someone you want starting for Week 8, even in the deepest of leagues. Look elsewhere for your Week 8 DB4/flex2.

Williams was excellent in Week 7, tallying three solos, five assists, one fumble recovery, and one pass defended. Evan has been inconsistent in the solo department, managing more than three solos just three times in six games, with four or more in just two. Still, he has put together some solid fantasy outings due to some peripheral contributions, keeping him in the DB3 mix. Treat him as a top-26 option for a plus Week 8 matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers on Sunday Night Football.

Stephens showed up in Week 7, racking up five solos and two passes defended. Stephens has recorded five or more solos in four of his last five contests and is a strong CB1/DB3 option while he's cooking. Treat him as such for a plus Week 8 matchup against the Cincinnati Bengals.

Ashtyn showed up in Week 7, tallying six solos, one assist, and one tackle for loss. It was Davis' first game with more than three solos all season. He played every snap for the third time in the last five games (while playing over 83 percent in the two others), but has not produced enough to be fantasy relevant outside of the bye weeks. With that said, the Dolphins have a plus Week 8 matchup on tap against the Atlanta Falcons, putting him on the map as a DB3/4 option.

Kool-Aid was excellent in Week 7, racking up five solos, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. McKinstry has recorded four or more solos in four of his seven contests and has four spike weeks to his name, including three in his last four games. Tap Kool-Aid as a DB3 option for Week 8, thanks to his hot play and a plus matchup against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.

Sigle has seen his snaps drop for the second straight week, bottoming out at 31 percent on Sunday night. Marques appears to be in a three-way platoon opposite Malik Mustapha and can no longer be trusted in lineups. Sigle saw just 60 percent of the Week 6 maps after playing every snap for the first five weeks, but this week's snap share suggests that he is no longer a starting option for the 49ers. Keep him out of lineups for Week 8, despite the plus matchup against the Houston Texans.

Rayshawn was excellent in Week 7, racking up two solos, one assist, one fumble recovery, one interception, and one pass defended. Jenkins played a season-high 40 percent of the snaps in Week 7, with the recovery coming on the special teams unit. He has not played enough to warrant plugging into lineups despite the strong Week 7 production. Look elsewhere for your Week 8 DB3.

Jaycee went off in Week 7, reeling off one assist, two interceptions, and two passes defended. Jaycee picked off Tyrod Taylor twice for his second and third interceptions of the season. Horn has been pretty quiet outside of the three picks, managing more than two solos just once and finishing with zero each time. Look elsewhere for Week 8 despite the plus matchup against the Buffalo Bills.
